cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.MM, cs.NE 

This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the problem of human pose estimation. Additionally, the use of generative adversarial networks (GANs) as the learning paradigm suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also involves the use of stacked hourglass networks, which are commonly used in multimedia (cs.MM) applications. Finally, the use of back-propagation and adversarial loss suggests that it may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
